How to Use Autopsy 4.2.1 for Digital Forensics

Introduction

Autopsy is an open-source digital forensics platform used to analyze disk images, recover files, and investigate cyber incidents. Version 4.2.1, though slightly older, still provides powerful forensic capabilities. This guide will walk you through the basic use of Autopsy 4.2.1.

Prerequisites

Before using Autopsy, ensure you have:

A computer running Windows or Linux

Autopsy 4.2.1 installed

Disk images or storage media to analyze

Installation

Download Autopsy 4.2.1 from the official repository or a trusted source.

Install the software by following the on-screen instructions.

Launch Autopsy from the Start Menu or Terminal.

Creating a New Case

Open Autopsy and select Create New Case.

Enter a case name, number, and examiner details.

Choose a location to store the case files.

Click Finish to create the case.

Adding Data Sources

Click Add Data Source in the Case Dashboard.

Select the type of data source:

Disk Image (E01, RAW, AFF)

Local Drive

Logical Files

Browse and select the image or device.

Click Next and select the modules you want to run (e.g., file analysis, keyword search).

Click Finish to start processing.

Performing Analysis

Once the data source is loaded, Autopsy will generate results.

File Browsing

Use the File Browser to navigate through the filesystem.

Check Deleted Files to recover lost data.

Keyword Search

Click on Keyword Search.

Enter the keyword(s) to look for.

Review the search results for relevant evidence.

Hash Analysis

Enable Hash Lookup in the Ingest Modules.

Compare files against known hash sets (e.g., NSRL).

Metadata Extraction

Use EXIF Metadata Viewer for images.

Check MFT (Master File Table) for NTFS file details.

Email and Internet History

Review Web History under the Extracted Content section.

Analyze Emails if applicable.

Reporting

Click Generate Report.

Choose HTML, CSV, XML, or PDF.

Customize the report contents.

Click Generate to save the report.

Conclusion

Autopsy 4.2.1 remains a powerful tool for digital forensic analysis. By following these steps, you can efficiently investigate disk images, extract valuable evidence, and generate comprehensive reports.
